2. Theoretical Foundation: The Three Capacities

We anchor our decomposition in distributed cognition (Hutchins 1995). Hutchins argues that any cognitive system operating at a societal scale must support three fundamental functions:

· Information Storage Capacity (ISC) – the ability to preserve knowledge beyond individual lifetimes via external representations (writing, archives, etc.).
· Technological Production Capacity (TPC) – the ability to create and deploy tools that extend human action.
· Social Coordination Capacity (SCC) – the ability to organize collective action across individuals.

These three are logically necessary: without storage, knowledge decays; without production, no material impact; without coordination, no large‑scale action. Moreover, they are a sufficient basis for modeling the key feedback loops that drive civilizational development. While additional dimensions (e.g., resource extraction) could be added, the triad captures the core interactions that have been central to historical trajectories. The model is presented as a minimal but complete framework for studying collective cognitive dynamics.

